==Old English==

===Etymology===
Common Germanic, from Indo-European ''*seks, *sweks'' ‘six’.  Cognate with Old High German [[sehs]] (German [[sechs]]), Old Saxon [[sehs]] (Dutch [[zes]]), Old Norse [[sex]] (Swedish [[sex]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌰𐌹𐌷𐍃]]; and, outside the Germanic languages, with Greek [[ἕξ]], Latin [[sex]], Old Irish ''sē'' (Irish [[sé]]), Old Slavic ''šest’'' (Russian [[шесть]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /sieks/

===Noun===
'''siex''' (ordinal: '''syxta''')
# [[six]], [[6]]

